Charaka vs. Sushruta's Classification

Charaka focuses on two fundamental layers—Udakdhara (hydration) and Asrukdhara (blood circulation)—aligning with modern concepts of epidermal hydration and vascular supply. Sushruta, however, expands to seven layers, detailing their specific physiological functions like pigmentation, immunity, and regeneration.

Ayurvedic vs. Modern Skin Functions

  • Avabhasini: Resembles the stratum corneum, responsible for skin radiance and hydration.
  • Lohita: Aligns with the dermal vasculature, influencing moles, naevi, and angiomas.
  • Shweta & Tamra: Roles in pigmentation and immune defense, comparable to melanocytes and dermal immunity.
  • Vedini: Sensory role parallels nerve endings in the dermis responsible for pain and touch.
  • Rohini & Mansadhara: Focus on healing, regeneration, and structural support, similar to fibroblasts and collagen networks.

Ayurvedic Disease Correlations with Modern Dermatology

  • Sidhma & Kilas Kushta (Ayurveda) → Pityriasis Versicolor & Vitiligo (Modern): Links to pigmentary disorders, fungal infections, and autoimmune depigmentation.
  • Dadru & Kushtha (Ayurveda) → Ringworm & Leprosy (Modern): Suggests immune dysfunction and Ayurveda’s immune-protective role of skin layers.
  • Alaji & Vidradhi (Ayurveda) → Boils & Abscess (Modern): Deep-seated infections aligned with immune defense functions.
